"proposed_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-101\nTITLE: ELECTRONIC RECORDS AND SYSTEM ACCESS CONTROL\nVERSION: 2.0\nEFFECTIVE DATE: [Insert Date]\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure establishes the administrative, technical, and physical controls to ensure system security, access control, electronic record integrity, and transmission security in compliance with FDA 21 CFR Part 11 and the FDA binding regulatory update Docket No. FDA-2026-N-8841. It ensures that electronic records are trustworthy, reliable, and generally equivalent to paper records.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all computer systems, network domains, and software tools that generate, maintain, modify, retrieve, transmit, or store quality records. It covers all electronic records and the systems that manage them, including data in transit.\n\n3.0 SYSTEM ACCESS CONTROLS\n3.1 Password Complexity: User passwords must be a minimum of 8 characters, containing at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one numeric digit, and one special character. The system shall enforce this complexity requirement.\n3.2 Password Aging: Passwords must be changed every 90 days. The system shall enforce password history to prevent reuse of the last five (5) passwords. Users shall be notified 14 days prior to expiration.\n3.3 Session Timeout: Computer terminals and software applications must automatically log out a user or lock the display terminal after 15 minutes of continuous keyboard or mouse inactivity. This timeout is not overrideable.\n3.4 Account Lockout: If a user enters an incorrect password three (3) consecutive times, the system will automatically lock the user account for 30 minutes. Account unlock requests must be approved by the IT System Administrator.\n3.5 User Privileges: All write, modification, and approval privileges are strictly restricted according to user roles. Authority checks must be performed before any transaction is executed.\n\n4.0 ENCRYPTION OF RECORDS IN TRANSMISSION\nAll electronic records transmitted over internal or external networks must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher. This applies to any data exchange between systems, including remote access, file transfers, and system integrations.\n\n5.0 AUDIT TRAIL\nThe system shall maintain a computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail that records the date, time, and author of all actions that create, modify, or delete electronic records. The audit trail must be secure, unalterable, and retained for the same period as the associated records. Regular reviews of audit trails shall be conducted to detect unauthorized activities.\n\n6.0 DUAL-AUTHORIZATION APPROVALS\nAll modifications to Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) and document releases require strict dual-authorization. Two authorized individuals, each with appropriate signing authority, must independently review and approve the change before it becomes effective. Electronic signatures used for these approvals must comply with SOP-102 (Electronic Signatures and Signing Authority).\n\n7.0 COMPLIANCE AND TRAINING\nAll personnel with access to systems covered by this SOP must receive training on these controls and their responsibilities. Training records shall be maintained.\n\n8.0 REVISION HISTORY\n[To be filled]",
"citations": [
"21 CFR Part 11.10",
"21 CFR Part 11.30",
"FDA-2026-N-8841"
],
"rationale": "The original SOP-101 lacked several controls mandated by the new regulation update (FDA-2026-N-8841). The following changes were made to achieve full compliance:\n- Session timeout reduced from 30 minutes to 15 minutes (per regulation requirement 2).\n- Added password aging (90-day expiration, history of 5) to meet requirement 1.\n- Added encryption of records in transit using TLS 1.3 (requirement 3).\n- Added a comprehensive audit trail section requiring computer-generated, time-stamped logs of all record creation, modification, or deletion (requirement 4).\n- Added dual-authorization approvals for SOP modifications and document releases (requirement 5).\n- Updated purpose and scope to reflect the new regulatory references and expanded coverage to data transmission.\nThe existing account lockout after 3 failed attempts already satisfied requirement 1, and password complexity was retained. All revisions are directly linked to the cited regulations and the binding docket."
