"proposed_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-103\nTITLE: SYSTEM AUDIT TRAILS AND DATA INTEGRITY\nVERSION: 2.0\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure establishes the requirements for the generation, protection, review, and retention of computer-generated audit trails, and defines the system security controls necessary to ensure the trustworthiness, reliability, and integrity of electronic records in compliance with FDA 21 CFR Part 11 and applicable guidelines.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all computer systems, network domains, and software applications that create, modify, delete, store, or transmit electronic records subject to GxP regulations. It encompasses database transactional logging, operating system log files, analytical metadata stores, and any other time-stamped audit trail mechanisms.\n\n3.0 SYSTEM ACCESS CONTROLS\n3.1 Password Aging: User passwords must be changed at least every 90 days. The system shall enforce password history to prevent reuse of the previous 5 passwords.\n3.2 Account Lockout: After three (3) consecutive failed login attempts, the user account shall be automatically locked. Account unlock shall require intervention by a system administrator following identity verification.\n3.3 Session Timeout: All user sessions shall be automatically terminated after 15 minutes of continuous keyboard or mouse inactivity. The system must lock the display and require re-authentication to resume.\n\n4.0 ENCRYPTION OF TRANSMITTED RECORDS\nAll electronic records transmitted over any network, including internal segments, must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher. Unencrypted transmission of GxP records is prohibited.\n\n5.0 AUDIT TRAIL MANAGEMENT\n5.1 Automatic Generation: Audit trails must be automatically generated by the system and capture all record creation, modification, and deletion events. Each entry shall include the date, time (synchronized to a trusted time source), user identity, and a description of the action performed.\n5.2 Immutability: Audit trails must be secured against modifications, edits, or deletion by any user, including system administrators and database developers. The system architecture must preclude any facility to pause, disable, or rewrite logged metadata.\n5.3 Regular Review: System audit trails must be reviewed by the Quality Assurance (QA) Department at least once every 30 calendar days. The review must be exhaustive, and evidence of review shall be documented via a cryptographically signed electronic audit attestation log.\n5.4 Retention: Audit trails must be retained for a duration no less than the retention requirements of the electronic records they document, and in a format that ensures readability and integrity throughout the retention period.\n\n6.0 DUAL-AUTHORIZATION FOR SOP MODIFICATIONS AND DOCUMENT RELEASES\nAny modification to this SOP or any other GxP document, as well as the release of such documents, shall require electronic approval by at least two authorized individuals. The system must enforce a dual-signature workflow, capturing the date, time, and identity of each approver in the audit trail.\n\n7.0 COMPLIANCE\nFailure to adhere to this SOP may result in regulatory non-compliance and disciplinary action. All personnel are responsible for reporting any suspected violations or system anomalies to QA immediately.",
"citations": [
"21 CFR Part 11.10(b)",
"21 CFR Part 11.10(d)",
"21 CFR Part 11.10(f)",
"21 CFR Part 11.30"
],
"rationale": "The original SOP-103 addressed only basic audit trail generation, immutability, review, and retention. The new regulation update mandates additional system security controls to ensure electronic record trustworthiness. The revised SOP incorporates: (1) password aging and account lockout after 3 failed attempts (21 CFR Part 11.10(d)) to prevent unauthorized access; (2) session timeout after 15 minutes of inactivity (21 CFR Part 11.10(d)) to mitigate unattended session risks; (3) encryption of transmitted records using TLS 1.3 (21 CFR Part 11.30) to protect data in transit; (4) explicit audit trail content requirements (date, time, user, action) per 21 CFR Part 11.10(b); (5) cryptographic sign-off for audit trail reviews to enhance integrity; and (6) dual-authorization approvals for SOP modifications and document releases (21 CFR Part 11.10(f)) to enforce authority checks. These changes ensure full compliance with the updated FDA guidelines and align the SOP with current regulatory expectations for data integrity and electronic record security."
}
