"proposed_text": "STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-110\nTITLE: BATCH RECORD REVIEW AND QUALITY RELEASE\nVERSION: 2\nEFFECTIVE DATE: [Insert Date]\nREVIEW CYCLE: Triennial\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure governs the systematic review of Batch Manufacturing Records (BMR) and analytical testing records to ensure batches conform to specifications before final release to market. It establishes the controls necessary to maintain the trustworthiness, reliability, and equivalence of electronic records and signatures in compliance with FDA Docket No. FDA-2026-N-8841 and 21 CFR Part 11.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all commercial batches of drug substances and drug products manufactured by BioPharma Corp. It encompasses all electronic systems used for batch record creation, review, approval, and release, including the electronic batch record (eBR) system, laboratory information management system (LIMS), and quality management software (eQMS).\n\n3.0 DEFINITIONS\n3.1 Electronic Batch Record (eBR): A computer-generated, time-stamped record that documents all manufacturing steps, in-process controls, and quality checks for a specific batch.\n3.2 Dual-Authorization: A process requiring the independent approval of two distinct authorized individuals before a document or batch is released.\n3.3 Audit Trail: A secure, computer-generated, time-stamped electronic log that records the date, time, and author of all actions that create, modify, or delete electronic records.\n\n4.0 RESPONSIBILITIES\n4.1 Manufacturing Supervisor: Reviews the completed BMR for completeness, accuracy, and compliance.\n4.2 Quality Assurance (QA) Manager: Provides final release authorization as part of the dual-authorization process.\n4.3 QA Senior Reviewer: Acts as the second authorizer in the dual-authorization release workflow.\n4.4 IT Department: Ensures that all electronic systems comply with the technical controls specified in Section 5.1.\n\n5.0 PROCEDURE\n5.1 System Security and Data Integrity Controls\nThe electronic systems used for batch record review and release must enforce the following controls, as mandated by FDA-2026-N-8841:\n5.1.1 Password Aging and Account Lockout: User passwords must expire every 90 days. After three (3) consecutive failed login attempts, the account shall be automatically locked for a minimum of 30 minutes. Unlock requires IT intervention.\n5.1.2 Session Timeout: Automated termination of an idle session must occur after 15 minutes of keyboard or mouse inactivity.\n5.1.3 Encryption: All electronic records transmitted between systems or over networks must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher.\n5.1.4 Audit Trail: The system must maintain a computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail that records the date, time, and author of every action that creates, modifies, or deletes electronic records. Audit trails must be retained for the same period as the associated records and be readily available for FDA inspection.\n\n5.2 Batch Record Audit\nThe manufacturing supervisor shall review the completed eBR, verifying that all entries are complete, calculations are correct, and electronic signatures are in place. The supervisor must confirm that the audit trail shows no unauthorized modifications. Any discrepancies must be documented as deviations.\n\n5.3 Deviation Review\nAll deviations, failures, and out-of-specification (OOS) investigations associated with the batch must be resolved and closed by QA before final batch release. The closure must be recorded in the eBR with an electronic signature and linked to the deviation report.\n\n5.4 QA Certificate of Analysis (CoA)\nAnalytical test results must match standard release specifications. A CoA must be compiled and signed off by the Quality Control lab using a dual-factor electronic signature (e.g., password plus biometric or token). The CoA is attached to the batch record in the eBR system.\n\n5.5 Dual-Authorization Batch Release\nThe final release decision requires strict dual-authorization. The QA Manager and a QA Senior Reviewer must independently review the complete batch record, including the audit trail, and each must execute their individual electronic signature to approve the release. The system shall record both approvals in the audit trail with a time stamp. The batch is not released until both signatures are obtained. This dual-authorization process applies to all batch releases and any subsequent SOP modifications related to the release process.\n\n5.6 Audit Trail Review Prior to Release\nBefore executing the release signatures, QA must perform a review of the batch record audit trail to ensure that all data entries, modifications, and deletions are legitimate and properly authorized. Any suspicious activity must be investigated and resolved.\n\n6.0 REFERENCES\n- SOP-IT-101: Electronic Records and System Access Control\n- SOP-QA-204: Electronic Signatures and Signing Authority\n- FDA Docket No. FDA-2026-N-8841\n- 21 CFR Part 11\n\n7.0 REVISION HISTORY\nVersion 1: Initial release.\nVersion 2: Added system security controls (password aging, account lockout, session timeout, encryption, audit trail) and dual-authorization requirement for batch release to comply with FDA-2026-N-8841.",
