CONFIDENTIAL - FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY

NEXUS BIOPHARMA
STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE
Electronic Signatures and Signing Authority
Document ID: SOP-102
Version: 2.0
Effective Date: [Insert Date]
Review Cycle: Triennial

1.0 PURPOSE
This procedure defines the administrative, technical, and procedural controls for electronic signatures to ensure they are the legally binding equivalent of handwritten signatures, and that the systems used to execute them are secure, reliable, and compliant with 21 CFR Part 11 and FDA-2026-N-8841.

2.0 SCOPE
This SOP applies to all electronic signatures executed on GxP records, including standard operating procedures, validation plans, clinical reports, batch release records, electronic batch records (eBR), design history files (DHF), and electronic quality management system (eQMS) documents. It also governs the system security controls that protect the integrity and confidentiality of these signatures and the associated electronic records.

3.0 DEFINITIONS
3.1 Electronic Signature: A computer data compilation of any symbol or series of symbols executed, adopted, or authorized by an individual to be the legally binding equivalent of the individual's handwritten signature.
3.2 Dual-Factor Authentication: A security process that requires two distinct identification components from independent categories of credentials.
3.3 Audit Trail: A computer-generated, time-stamped log that records the date, time, and author of all actions that create, modify, or delete electronic records.

4.0 ELECTRONIC SIGNATURE REQUIREMENTS
4.1 Dual-Factor Authentication
The execution of an electronic signature requires the input of two distinct identification components: a unique user ID and password, or a biometric identifier combined with password authentication. This ensures that the signature is uniquely linked to the signer.
[21 CFR Part 11.200(a), 11.200(b)]

4.2 Signature Manifestation
Every electronically signed document must visually display the following three signature components:
- The printed name of the signer.
- The date and time stamp in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) when the signature was executed.
- The meaning associated with the signature (e.g., Review, Approval, Authorship, or Responsibility).
[21 CFR Part 11.50]

4.3 Non-Repudiation
Electronic signatures shall be unique to one individual and shall not be copied, reassigned, or transferred. No two individuals shall share signing credentials. The system must employ cryptographic or logical locks to bind the signature to the record, ensuring that any subsequent record modification invalidates the existing signature.
[21 CFR Part 11.200(a), 11.10(e)]

4.4 Electronic Signature Affirmation
Prior to granting electronic signing privileges, the Quality Assurance organization must obtain a signed, written statement from the employee certifying that their electronic signatures are the legally binding equivalent of their handwritten signature. This physical document shall be archived indefinitely.
[21 CFR Part 11.100(c)]

5.0 SYSTEM SECURITY CONTROLS
5.1 Password Management
5.1.1 Password Complexity: User passwords must be a minimum of 8 characters, containing at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one numeric digit, and one special character.
5.1.2 Password Aging: Passwords must be changed every 90 days. The system shall enforce this by prompting the user to change the password upon expiration.
5.1.3 Account Lockout: If a user enters an incorrect password three (3) consecutive times, the system will automatically lock the user account for 30 minutes. Account unlock requires intervention by the System Administrator following identity verification.
[21 CFR Part 11.300(b), 11.300(d)]

5.2 Session Timeout
All computer terminals and software applications that handle electronic records or signatures must automatically log out the user or lock the display after 15 minutes of continuous keyboard or mouse inactivity. This prevents unauthorized access during unattended sessions.
[21 CFR Part 11.300(d), 11.10(d)]

5.3 Encryption of Transmitted Records
All electronic records and signatures transmitted over any network (internal or external) must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher. This ensures the confidentiality and integrity of data in transit.
[21 CFR Part 11.10(k)]

6.0 AUDIT TRAIL
6.1 Computer-Generated Audit Trail
The system must maintain a secure, computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail that independently records the date, time (UTC), and author of all actions that create, modify, or delete electronic records. The audit trail shall be retained for a period at least as long as the associated record retention period and must be readily available for FDA review.
6.2 Audit Trail Integrity
Audit trail records shall be protected from modification or deletion. Any changes to the audit trail must be documented and justified, with the original entry preserved.
[21 CFR Part 11.10(e)]

7.0 DUAL-AUTHORIZATION FOR SOP MODIFICATIONS AND DOCUMENT RELEASES
7.1 Dual-Authorization Requirement
All modifications to standard operating procedures (SOPs) and the release of GxP documents (e.g., batch records, validation reports) require the approval of at least two authorized individuals. The system must enforce this by requiring two distinct electronic signatures, each with the meaning "Approval" or "Author", before the document becomes effective.
7.2 Authority Checks
The system shall verify that each signer has the appropriate authority and training to perform the approval. A list of authorized signers for each document type shall be maintained by Quality Assurance.
[21 CFR Part 11.10(f)]

8.0 TRAINING AND ACCOUNTABILITY
All personnel who use electronic signatures must receive training on this SOP and the relevant system procedures. Training records shall be documented. Individuals are accountable for all actions taken under their electronic signatures.
[21 CFR Part 11.10(i), 11.10(j)]

9.0 REFERENCES
- 21 CFR Part 11: Electronic Records; Electronic Signatures
- FDA-2026-N-8841
- SOP-101: Electronic Records and System Access Control
- SOP-VAL-312: System Audit Trails and Data Integrity

10.0 REVISION HISTORY
Version 1.0: Initial release.
Version 2.0: Revised to incorporate system security controls, audit trail, encryption, dual-authorization, and password aging per updated FDA guidelines.

That's the proposed_text. The original_text is the exact text provided. We'll copy that. The citations list as above. The rationale: The original SOP-102 only addressed basic signature components and non-repudiation, lacking the system security controls, audit trail, encryption, and dual-authorization now mandated by the updated regulation. The revised SOP integrates these requirements, ensuring full compliance with 21 CFR Part 11 and FDA-2026-N-8841, and aligns with internal QMS documents SOP-101 and SOP-VAL-312. Each new section is directly linked to specific regulatory citations.
