 a signed, written statement from the employee certifying that their system signatures represent the legally binding equivalent of their handwritten signature. This physical document must be archived indefinitely. NEXUS BIOPHARMA INC. | QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM Page 2 of 5 CONFIDENTIAL - FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY NEXUS BIOPHARMA STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE System Audit Trails and Data Integrity Document ID: SOP-VAL-312 Version: 6.0 Effective Date: [Insert Date] Review Cycle: Triennial 1.0 PURPOSE This document mandates the design, retention, and verification mechanisms for computer-generated, time-stamped system audit trails to preserve complete data lineage and trace all GxP lifecycle modifications, in compliance with FDA-2026-N-8841. 2.0 SCOPE This standard governs all database transactional logging, operating system log files, and analytical metadata stores within the company's\n\n[4] 997b9f58-cce0-4a86-950f-1ed7d39a6c26 (relevance: 80.6%):\nmanagement software (eQMS). 3.0 PROCEDURE & REQUIREMENTS 3.1 Dual-Component Authentication Framework: Electronic signatures not executed during a single continuous logged session must necessitate the active entry of two distinct authentication components: a unique user alphanumeric identifier and an encrypted passphrase. 3.2 Mandatory Manifestation of Intent Meta-Data: Every signature instance must automatically inject and hardcode clear metadata strings directly into the non-volatile record block, stating explicitly: the printed name of the signer, the precise coordinated universal time (UTC) date stamp, and the legally binding meaning or intent (e.g., Review, Approval, Authorship). 3.3 Signature-to-Record Co-location: Validated technical frameworks must execute a cryptographic or logical lock binding the electronic signature string directly to its respective record payload. The metadata must be structurally unalterable, ensuring that any subsequent record modifications automatically invalidate the existing electronic manifest. 3.4 Electronic Signature Affirmation Notification: Prior to granting individual electronic signing privileges, the Quality Assurance organization must secure\n\n[5] 997b9f58-cce0-4a86-950f-1ed7d39a6c26 (relevance: 80.1%):\n(4) clock hours from initial engineering identification. The incident response team shall follow the internal incident management protocol (SOP-IT-103) to ensure timely detection, containment, and reporting. NEXUS BIOPHARMA INC. | QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM Page 1 of 5 CONFIDENTIAL - FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY NEXUS BIOPHARMA STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE Electronic Signatures and Signing Authority Document ID: SOP-QA-204 Version: 3.1 Effective Date: 04-Mar-2025 Review Cycle: Triennial 1.0 PURPOSE This procedure defines the administrative framework, compliance controls, and legal execution workflows necessary to implement electronic signatures that are legally equivalent to traditional holographic ink signatures on regulatory documents. 2.0 SCOPE This standard encompasses all electronic approvals, attestations, and authentications executed within electronic batch records (eBR), product design history files (DHF), and electronic quality management software (eQMS). 3.0 PROCEDURE & REQUIREMENTS 3.1 Dual-Component Authentication Framework: Electronic signatures not executed during a single continuous logged session must necessitate the active entry of two distinct authentication\n\n---\nGround your response in the above context. Do not fabricate citations or references not present in the retrieved documents.\n\nYou MUST respond with a SINGLE valid JSON object matching this schema (no markdown code fences, no extra text outside the JSON):\n{\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"proposed_text\": {\n      \"title\": \"Proposed Text\",\n      \"type\": \"string\"\n    },\n    \"citations\": {\n      \"items\": {\n        \"type\": \"string\"\n      },\n      \"title\": \"Citations\",\n      \"type\": \"array\"\n    },\n    \"rationale\": {\n      \"title\": \"Rationale