 11.10(f)?), dual-authorization for SOP modifications (11.10(f) authority checks). So we can cite these.\n\nWe need to produce a complete revised SOP-102 that incorporates all these requirements. The original SOP-102 had sections: Purpose, Scope, Electronic Signature Requirements (3.1 Dual-Factor, 3.2 Manifestation, 3.3 Non-Repudiation). We'll keep those but add new sections for System Security Controls (password aging, lockout, session timeout, encryption), Audit Trail, and Dual-Authorization for SOP Modifications. Also, we need to ensure the signature manifestation includes UTC time stamp as per the retrieved context (SOP-VAL-312 mentions UTC). The original SOP-102 says \"date and time stamp (including time zone)\" which is fine, but we can specify UTC. The retrieved context from SOP-VAL-312 says \"precise coordinated universal time (UTC) date stamp\". So we can align with that. Also, the dual-factor signature: the original says \"unique user ID and password, or a biometric identifier combined with password authentication.\" That's fine. The new regulation doesn't change that. But we need to add password aging and lockout. So we'll add a section on Password Management: passwords must be changed every 90 days (aging), and account lockout after 3 failed attempts. Session timeout: 15 minutes of inactivity. Encryption: all records transmitted must use TLS 1.3. Audit trail: computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail for all actions on electronic records. Dual-authorization: any SOP modification or document release requires approval by two authorized individuals. We'll incorporate these into the SOP.\n\nWe'll structure the revised SOP as:\n\nSTANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE: SOP-102\nTITLE: ELECTRONIC SIGNATURES AND SIGNING AUTHORITY\nVERSION: 2 (or we can keep version 1 but it's revised, so version 2)\nEffective Date: [today]\nReview Cycle: Triennial\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\n... (similar but expanded to include compliance with 21 CFR Part 11 and the new regulation)\n\n2.0 SCOPE\n... (expanded to include all systems that use electronic signatures, and the controls for those systems)\n\n3.0 DEFINITIONS (maybe add)\n\n4.0 ELECTRONIC SIGNATURE REQUIREMENTS\n4.1 Dual-Factor Authentication (same as 3.1)\n4.2 Signature Manifestation (same as 3.2 but specify UTC)\n4.3 Non-Repudiation (same as 3.3)\n4.4 Password Management (new: aging, complexity, lockout)\n4.5 Session Timeout (new: 15 minutes)\n4.6 Encryption (new: TLS 1.3 for transmission)\n4.7 Audit Trail (new: computer-generated, time-stamped, records all actions)\n4.8 Dual-Authorization for SOP Modifications and Document Releases (new)\n\n5.0 TRAINING AND ACCOUNTABILITY\n6.0 REFERENCES\n\nWe'll cite the relevant 21 CFR Part 11 sections. The retrieved context includes SOP-101 which has password complexity, session timeout 30 min, account lockout 30 min. But the new regulation says 15 min timeout and lockout after 3 attempts (no duration specified, but we can set a lockout period). We'll set lockout for 30 minutes as per SOP-101, but the regulation just says lockout after 3 failed attempts, so that's fine. Password aging: we'll add a requirement to change passwords every 90 days. The regulation says \"password aging\", so we'll implement that.\n\nWe'll also incorporate the requirement from the retrieved context about electronic signature affirmation notification (SOP-VAL-312 section 3.4) which is a written statement from the employee. That's a good practice and aligns with 21 CFR Part 11.100(c) (certification). So we'll add that.\n\nNow, the output must be a JSON with proposed_text (the full revised SOP), original_text (the exact original SOP), citations (list of 21 CFR Part 11 citations), and rationale. The original_text is the exact text of SOP-102 as provided. So we'll copy that. The proposed_text will be the full revised SOP. The citations will be the specific 21 CFR Part 11 sections that correspond to the changes. The rationale will explain the changes.\n\nWe need to ensure the proposed_text is a complete standalone document. So we'll write it in full.\n\nLet's craft the revised SOP.\n\nWe'll use the header from the retrieved context: NEXUS BIOPHARMA INC. | QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM, etc. But the original SOP-102 didn't have that header. The target document is just the text. We can add a header to make it look like a proper SOP. The retrieved context shows SOP-101 and SOP-VAL-312 with headers. So we'll include a header: NEXUS BIOPHARMA INC. | QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM, Page 1 of X, CONFIDENTIAL, etc. But the original didn't have that. The prompt says \"generate a complete, revised, compliant SOP document from start to finish.\" So we can include a proper header. We'll model it after SOP-101. We'll set version to 2.0, effective date as today's date (we can use a placeholder like [Insert Date] or a specific date). The regulation update doesn't specify a date, so we'll use [Insert Date] or today's date. I'll use [Insert Date] to be safe.\n\nNow, the citations: We'll cite 21 CFR Part 11.10(d) for access controls (password aging, lockout, session timeout), 11.10(e) for audit trail, 11.10(f) for authority checks (dual authorization), 11.10(k) for encryption (open systems), 11.200(a) for uniqueness, 11.200(b) for identity verification, 11.300(b) for periodic password changes, 11.300(d) for transaction safeguards (session timeout), 11.300(e) for device testing? Not needed. We'll pick the most relevant ones. The regulation update mentions \"password aging and account lockout after 3 consecutive failed login attempts\" -> 11.300(b) and 11.300(d) (loss management). \"Automated session timeout/inactivity termination after 15 minutes\" -> 11.300(d) or 11.10(d). \"Encryption of records during transmission using TLS 1.3\" -> 11.10(k) for open systems, but if it's a closed system, encryption might be under 11.10 generally. We'll cite 11.10(k) as it's about transmission. \"Maintaining a computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail\" -> 11.10(e). \"Strict dual-authorization approvals for all SOP modifications and document releases\" -> 11.10(f) (authority checks). Also, the signature manifestation and non-repudiation are from 11.50 (signature manifestations) and 11.200. So we'll include those.\n\nSo citations: [\"21 CFR Part 11.10(d)\", \"21 CFR Part 11.10(e)\", \"21 CFR Part 11.10(f)\", \"21 CFR Part 11.10(k)\", \"21 CFR Part 11.50\", \"21 CFR Part 11.200(a)\", \"21 CFR Part 11.200(b)\", \"21 CFR Part 11.300(b)\", \"21 CFR Part 11.300(d)\"]. We'll list them.\n\nRationale: Explain that the original SOP lacked system security controls, audit trail, encryption, and dual-authorization, which are now required by the updated regulation. The revised SOP incorporates these to ensure electronic signatures are trustworthy and equivalent to paper records, in compliance with 21 CFR Part 11.\n\nNow, write the proposed_text. We'll include the header, then the sections. We'll keep the original sections but renumber them. We'll add new sections. We'll also add a section for \"Electronic Signature Affirmation\" as per the retrieved context, which is a good practice and aligns with 11.100(c). The regulation update didn't explicitly mention it, but it's part of the retrieved knowledge base and is a requirement for non-repudiation. So we'll include it.\n\nLet's draft:\n\nNEXUS BIOPHARMA INC. | QUALITY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM\nPage 1 of 6\nCONFIDENTIAL - FOR INTERNAL USE ONLY\n\nNEXUS BIOPHARMA\nSTANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE\nElectronic Signatures and Signing Authority\nDocument ID: SOP-102\nVersion: 2.0\nEffective Date: [Insert Date]\nReview Cycle: Triennial\n\n1.0 PURPOSE\nThis procedure defines the administrative, technical, and procedural controls for electronic signatures to ensure they are the legally binding equivalent of handwritten signatures, and that the systems used to execute them are secure, reliable, and compliant with 21 CFR Part 11 and FDA-2026-N-8841.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\nThis SOP applies to all electronic signatures executed on GxP records, including standard operating procedures, validation plans, clinical reports, batch release records, electronic batch records (eBR), design history files (DHF), and electronic quality management system (eQMS) documents. It also governs the system security controls that protect the integrity and confidentiality of these signatures and the associated electronic records.\n\n3.0 DEFINITIONS\n3.1 Electronic Signature: A computer data compilation of any symbol or series of symbols executed, adopted, or authorized by an individual to be the legally binding equivalent of the individual's handwritten signature.\n3.2 Dual-Factor Authentication: A security process that requires two distinct identification components from independent categories of credentials.\n3.3 Audit Trail: A computer-generated, time-stamped log that records the date, time, and author of all actions that create, modify, or delete electronic records.\n\n4.0 ELECTRONIC SIGNATURE REQUIREMENTS\n4.1 Dual-Factor Authentication\nThe execution of an electronic signature requires the input of two distinct identification components: a unique user ID and password, or a biometric identifier combined with password authentication. This ensures that the signature is uniquely linked to the signer.\n[21 CFR Part 11.200(a), 11.200(b)]\n\n4.2 Signature Manifestation\nEvery electronically signed document must visually display the following three signature components:\n- The printed name of the signer.\n- The date and time stamp in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) when the signature was executed.\n- The meaning associated with the signature (e.g., Review, Approval, Authorship, or Responsibility).\n[21 CFR Part 11.50]\n\n4.3 Non-Repudiation\nElectronic signatures shall be unique to one individual and shall not be copied, reassigned, or transferred. No two individuals shall share signing credentials. The system must employ cryptographic or logical locks to bind the signature to the record, ensuring that any subsequent record modification invalidates the existing signature.\n[21 CFR Part 11.200(a), 11.10(e)]\n\n4.4 Electronic Signature Affirmation\nPrior to granting electronic signing privileges, the Quality Assurance organization must obtain a signed, written statement from the employee certifying that their electronic signatures are the legally binding equivalent of their handwritten signature. This physical document shall be archived indefinitely.\n[21 CFR Part 11.100(c)]\n\n5.0 SYSTEM SECURITY CONTROLS\n5.1 Password Management\n5.1.1 Password Complexity: User passwords must be a minimum of 8 characters, containing at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one numeric digit, and one special character.\n5.1.2 Password Aging: Passwords must be changed every 90 days. The system shall enforce this by prompting the user to change the password upon expiration.\n5.1.3 Account Lockout: If a user enters an incorrect password three (3) consecutive times, the system will automatically lock the user account for 30 minutes. Account unlock requires intervention by the System Administrator following identity verification.\n[21 CFR Part 11.300(b), 11.300(d)]\n\n5.2 Session Timeout\nAll computer terminals and software applications that handle electronic records or signatures must automatically log out the user or lock the display after 15 minutes of continuous keyboard or mouse inactivity. This prevents unauthorized access during unattended sessions.\n[21 CFR Part 11.300(d), 11.10(d)]\n\n5.3 Encryption of Transmitted Records\nAll electronic records and signatures transmitted over any network (internal or external) must be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.3 or higher. This ensures the confidentiality and integrity of data in transit.\n[21 CFR Part 11.10(k)]\n\n6.0 AUDIT TRAIL\n6.1 Computer-Generated Audit Trail\nThe system must maintain a secure, computer-generated, time-stamped audit trail that independently records the date, time (UTC), and author of all actions that create, modify, or delete electronic records. The audit trail shall be retained for a period at least as long as the associated record retention period and must be readily available for FDA review.\n6.2 Audit Trail Integrity\nAudit trail records shall be protected from modification or deletion. Any changes to the audit trail must be documented and justified, with the original entry preserved.\n[21 CFR Part 11.10(e)]\n\n7.0 DUAL-AUTHORIZATION FOR SOP MODIFICATIONS AND DOCUMENT RELEASES\n7.1 Dual-Authorization Requirement\nAll modifications to standard operating procedures (SOPs) and the release of GxP documents (e.g., batch records, validation reports) require the approval of at least two authorized individuals. The system must enforce this by requiring two distinct electronic signatures, each with the meaning \"Approval\" or \"Author\", before the document becomes effective.\n7.2 Authority Checks\nThe system shall verify that each signer has the appropriate authority and training to perform the approval. A list of authorized signers for each document type shall be maintained by Quality Assurance.\n[21 CFR Part 11.10(f)]\n\n8.0 TRAINING AND ACCOUNTABILITY\nAll personnel who use electronic signatures must receive training on this SOP and the relevant system procedures. Training records shall be documented. Individuals are accountable for all actions taken under their electronic signatures.\n[21 CFR Part 11.10(i), 11.10(j)]\n\n9.0 REFERENCES\n- 21 CFR Part 11: Electronic Records; Electronic Signatures\n- FDA-2026-N-8841\n- SOP-101: Electronic Records and System Access Control\n- SOP-VAL-312: System Audit Trails and Data Integrity\n\n10.0 REVISION HISTORY\nVersion 1.0: Initial release.\nVersion 2.0: Revised to incorporate system security controls, audit trail, encryption, dual-authorization, and password aging per updated FDA guidelines.\n\nThat's the proposed_text. The original_text is the exact text provided. We'll copy that. The citations list as above. The rationale: The original SOP-102 only addressed basic signature components and non-repudiation, lacking the system security controls, audit trail, encryption, and dual-authorization now mandated by the updated regulation. The revised SOP integrates these requirements, ensuring full compliance with 21 CFR Part 11 and FDA-2026-N-8841, and aligns with internal QMS documents SOP-101 and SOP-VAL-312. Each new section is directly linked to specific regulatory citations."
